Java provides Queue as Interface in java.util package.
import java.util.Queue;

Common implementations:
âœ” LinkedList
âœ” ArrayDeque
âœ” PriorityQueue


ğŸ§© Types of Queue
1ï¸âƒ£ Simple Queue (Linear Queue)

Normal FIFO queue.

Example implementation:

Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
q.add(10);
q.add(20);
q.add(30);

System.out.println(q.poll()); // 10

2ï¸âƒ£ Circular Queue

Last position connects to first position (used to save space).

Used in:
âœ” CPU scheduling
âœ” Buffer memory

Java internal example: ArrayDeque behaves like circular array.

3ï¸âƒ£ Priority Queue

Elements removed based on priority, not insertion order.

PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();
pq.add(30);
pq.add(10);
pq.add(20);

System.out.println(pq.poll()); // 10 (smallest first)

4ï¸âƒ£ Deque (Double Ended Queue)

Insert/delete from both ends.

Deque<Integer> dq = new ArrayDeque<>();
dq.addFirst(10);
dq.addLast(20);
dq.removeFirst();

| Implementation | Storage Type | Extra Memory | Speed    |
| -------------- | ------------ | ------------ | -------- |
| LinkedList     | Nodes (heap) | High         | Medium   |
| ArrayDeque     | Array        | Low          | Fast     |
| PriorityQueue  | Heap (array) | Medium       | Log time |


